description:
In this episode, Dr. Sean Kennelly, of the Clinical and Research Advisory Panel for the Alzheimers Society of Ireland, looks at the benefit of exercise and education for our brains. Corrina Grimes of the Global Brain Health Institute uses her background in nutrition to describe a healthy diet to benefit the brain. Professor Suzanne Cahill, national director of the dementia services, information and development centre, delves into why people are slow to come forward for diagnosis.
Meanwhile, our reporter, Mairad Cleary, takes to the streets to see what the general public think they can do to prevent dementia.
title: Episode 6: Preventing Dementia

description:
In this episode, Professor Brian Lawlor, chairperson of the Understand Together Campaign Steering Committee, discusses the importance of exercise in improving brain health. Sinead Grennan, Chief Executive of Sonas APC, explains the importance of doing activities that are meaningful to the individual while architect Tom Grey looks at the practicalities of building an environment that enables someone to live well with dementia.
This weeks report looks at CareBrights Dementia Friendly Village in Bruff, Co. Limerick.
title: Episode 5: Dementia Friendly Spaces and Activities

description: In this episode, Fionnuala is joined by Helen Rochford Brennan, chairperson of the European Working Group of People with Dementia, Dominic Trepl, health economist and assistant professor at Trinity College Dublin and Dr. David Robinson, Consultant Physician in Geriatric Medicine in St. James Hospital, Dublin. Their discussion takes us on a journey from Helens first-hand experience, to the lack of funding for research and what we can do to improve our brain health now to reduce the risk of dementia later. Also included in this episode is a joyous report of the songs and stories from the The Forget Me Nots dementia friendly choir.
title: Episode 1: Deconstructing Dementia

description: In this episode, our host Fionnuala Sweeney hears the personal experience of carers from Nora Owen and Teresa OGrady Peyton, who care for their husbands. Also joining the panel is Chairperson of the Carers Campaign Network, Judy Williams who discusses the supports her network offers to carers on the front line. This weeks report gives a tour of the Alzheimers Society of Irelands Mobile Information Service.
title: Episode 2: Dementia and Carers

description: In this episode, Fionuala is joined by Mary Condell of Sage Advocacy, John Costello solicitor and author of Law and Finance in Retirement and Roma Ruddy, a volunteer at the Alzheimer Society of Ireland helpline. Joint bank accounts, the power of attorney, wills and the Assisted Decision Making Act are just some of the topics explained in this practical episode. This weeks report looks at the Think Ahead Programme by the Irish Hospice Society.
title: Episode 4: The Law and Dementia

description: In this episode, Fionnuala is joined by world advocate for dementia Professor Emeritus Steven Sabat, Professor Ian Robertson of Trinity College Dublin and Jacinta Dixon, a member of the Irish Dementia Working Group. The panel discusses the impact of isolation from a neuroscientific perspective and from personal experience. Also included in this programme is a report from the Alzheimers Caf in Donnybrook, Dublin.
title: Episode 3: Isolation and Stigma
